.com/image/347232853/?terms=Martinson%2BCramer</ref> \n|office4      = Chairman of the [[North Dakota Republican Party]]\n|term_start4  = July 1991\n|term_end4    = May 1993\n|predecessor4 = [[Layton Freborg]]\n|successor4   = [[John Korsmo]]\n|birth_name   = Kevin John Cramer\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1961|1|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Rolette, North Dakota|Rolette]], [[North Dakota]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education    = [[Concordia College (Moorhead, Minnesota)|Concordia College, Minnesota]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Mary]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n'''Kevin John Cramer''' (born January 21, 1961) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[North Dakota's at-large congressional district]] since 2013. Cramer previously chaired the [[North Dakota Republican Party]] (1991\u20131993) and served as State Tourism Director (1993\u20131997) and Economic Development Director (1997\u20132000). He served on the [[North Dakota Public Service Commission]] from 2003 to 2012.\n\nCramer is the Republican nominee in the [[United States Senate election in North Dakota, 2018|2018 U.S. Senate election in North Dakota]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCramer was born in [[Rolette, North Dakota]], the first of five children of Clarice (Hjelden) and Richard Cramer.<ref>http://boulgerfuneralhome.com/obituaries/richard-cramer/</ref> He was raised in [[Kindred, North Dakota]], in [[Cass County, North Dakota|Cass County]]. Cramer graduated from Kindred High School. He received a B.A. degree from [[Concordia College (Moorhead)|Concordia College]] in [[Moorhead, Minnesota]], in 1983. He earned a master's degree in management from the [[University of Mary]] in [[Bismarck, North Dakota]], in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kevincramer.org/meetkevin/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723222633/http://kevincramer.org/meetkevin/ |archivedate=2012-07-23 |title=Meet Kevin |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nAfter college, Cramer campaigned for an unsuccessful Republican tax commissioner candidate in 1984. In 1986, he campaigned for U.S. Senator [[Mark Andrews (politician)|Mark Andrews]]' bid for re-election. Andrews lost to [[North Dakota Democratic-Nonpartisan League Party]] [[U.S. Senator]] [[Kent Conrad]]. Conrad's party is the North Dakota affiliate of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]. Cramer went on to work for the state Republican Party.\n\nHe was the Chairman of the [[North Dakota Republican Party]] from 1991 to 1993. At age 30, he was the youngest person to be named state party chairman.\n\nIn 1993, Republican Governor [[Ed Schafer]] appointed Cramer to be State Tourism Director. He served in that position until he was appointed to become Economic Development Director in 1997. In 1996, House Majority Leader [[Dick Armey]] of Texas, a North Dakota native, persuaded Cramer to challenge Democratic U.S. Congressman [[Earl Pomeroy]] in [[North Dakota's at-large congressional district]]. Pomeroy defeated him 55%\u201343%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29648 |title=ND At-Large Race - Nov 05, 1996 |publisher=Our Campaigns |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref> In 1998, Cramer faced Pomeroy in a rematch. Pomeroy defeated him again, this time by a margin of 56%\u201341%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30807 |title=ND At-Large Race - Nov 03, 1998 |publisher=Our Campaigns |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his stint as Director of Economic Development, Cramer became Director of the Harold Schafer Leadership Foundation. He served in that position until he was appointed to the [[North Dakota Public Service Commission|Public Service Commission]] by Republican Governor [[John Hoeven]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ifill |first=Gwen |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/north-dakota-at-large-house-district-20121101 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107185352/http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/north-dakota-at-large-house-district-20121101 |archivedate=2012-11-07 |title=North Dakota, At-Large House District - NationalJournal.com |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref> Cramer was elected to a six-year term in 2004 when he defeated NPL nominee Ron Gumeringer 65%\u201335%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=179384 |title=ND Public Service Commissioner Race - Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nCramer co-chairs the Roughrider Honor Flight program. This program gives [[World War Two]] veterans the chance to visit the World War Two memorial in Washington, D.C. Cramer has worked to locate veterans and raise money for them to take part in the program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kxnet.com/getArticle.asp?AddComment=True&ArticleId=389580|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713174921/http://kxnet.com/getArticle.asp?AddComment=True&ArticleId=389580|archivedate=2011-07-13|title=Wayback Machine|date=13 July 2011|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2010, Cramer announced that he would run for the North Dakota seat in the [[United States House of Representatives]] in the [[United States House of Representatives election in North Dakota, 2010|2010 election]].<ref>[http://www.valleynewslive.tv/artman2/publish/local_regional_news/15885.shtml] {{dead link|date=January 2017}}</ref> Cramer was very visible in early 2010 at North Dakota town hall meetings, where he opposed health care legislation passed by the U.S. House in late 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bulletin.aarp.org/states/nd/2010/4/articles/town_hall_focuses_health_care.html |title=Daily News - Health, Money, Social Security, Medicare, Politics - Bulletin Today |website=Bulletin.aarp.org |date=2017-01-04 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref> Cramer attended numerous [[Tea party movement|Tea Party rallies]] in North Dakota, where he spoke about energy, taxes, jobs and the U.S. Constitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevincramer.org/news.asp?seq=46 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029192136/http://www.kevincramer.org/news.asp?seq=46 |archivedate=2010-10-29 |title=Kevin Cramer for North Dakota Public Service Commission (ndpsc) Re Election Campaign 2010 NDGOP Republican (kevincramer.org) |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref> He was unsuccessful in receiving the nomination at the state Republican Party convention in March 2010, losing to former House Majority Leader [[Rick Berg]].\n\nLater in 2010, Cramer won reelection to a second term to the Public Service Commission, defeating Democratic candidate Brad Crabtree 61%\u201335%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=656954 |title=ND Public Service Commissioner Race - Nov 02, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2013\u2013present)==\n[[File:Kevin Cramer, official portrait, 113th Congress.jpg|thumb|Cramer's first official portait]]\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2012====\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives election in North Dakota, 2012}}\n\nIn 2012, incumbent U.S. Representative [[Rick Berg]] decided to retire to run for the U.S. Senate. Cramer decided to run for the seat a fourth time.\n\nVarious national conservative groups, include [[FreedomWorks]] and the [[Club for Growth]], endorsed Cramer, while Berg endorsed Cramer's rival, fellow [[North Dakota Public Service Commission|Public Service Commissioner]] [[Brian Kalk]].<ref>Shira T. Center, [http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/north-dakota-rick-berg-backs-brian-kalk-for-his-house-seat North Dakota: Rick Berg Backs Brian Kalk for His House Seat], ''Roll Call'' (June 5, 2012).</ref> In the Republican [[primary election]] in June 2012, Cramer received 54,405 votes (54%) to Kalk's 45,415 votes (45%).<ref>[http://results.sos.nd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?eid=33&text=Race&type=SW&map=CTY  Official Results Primary Election - June 12, 2012], [[North Dakota Secretary of State]].</ref>\n\nIn the November 2012 general election, Cramer went on to defeat [[North Dakota Democratic-Nonpartisan League Party|Democratic-NPL]] State Representative [[Pam Gulleson]] in the general election, with Cramer receiving 173,585 votes (55%) to Gulleson's 131,870 votes (42%). [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] candidate Eric Olson received about 3% of the vote.<ref>[http://results.sos.nd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?eid=35&text=Race&type=SW&map=CTY  Official Results General Election - November 6, 2012],  [[North Dakota Secretary of State]].</ref>\n\nCramer was sworn in on January 3, 2013.<ref>Nick Smith, [http://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/heidi-heitkamp-kevin-cramer-sworn-into-office/article_6a85de4e-55fe-11e2-b386-0019bb2963f4.html Heidi Heitkamp, Kevin Cramer sworn into office], ''Bismarck Tribune'' (January 3, 2013).</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives election in North Dakota, 2014}}\n\nIn 2014, Cramer ran for reelection, running unopposed for renomination as the Republican candidate.<ref>[http://results.sos.nd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?eid=120&text=Race&type=SW&map=CTY  Official Results Primary Election - June 10, 2014], North Dakota Secretary of State.</ref>\n\nCramer won the general election with 55% of the vote, defeating Democratic-NPL nominee [[George B. Sinner]], who received 38%. A Libertarian candidate, Jack Seaman, received slightly under 6%.<ref>[http://results.sos.nd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?eid=126&text=Race&type=SW&map=CTY  Official Results General Election - November 4, 2014], North Dakota Secretary of State.</ref>\n\n====2016====\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives election in North Dakota, 2016}}\n\nIn 2016, Cramer sought election to a third term in Congress. He ran unopposed in the primary election and defeated Democratic-NPL nominee [[Chase Iron Eyes]], a Native American activist, in the general election.<ref>[http://results.sos.nd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?text=Race&type=SW&map=CTY Official Results Primary Election - June 14, 2016], North Dakota Secretary of State.</ref><ref>Mark Trahant, [http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2016/04/03/chase-iron-eyes-runs-north-dakota-out-necessity-164009 Chase Iron Eyes Runs In North Dakota Out of 'Necessity'], [[Indian Country Today Media Network]] (April 3, 2016).</ref>\n\n====2018 Senate campaign====\n{{Main|United States Senate election in North Dakota, 2018}}\n\nAfter months of speculation, Cramer announced on January 11, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|last=Miyoshi |first=Sheila |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/01/11/kevin-cramer-no-senate-in-north-dakota-336495 |title=Cramer won't run for Senate in North Dakota |publisher=Politico |date=2018-01-11 |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref> that he would not seek the Republican nomination for U.S. Senate to run against [[North Dakota Democratic-Nonpartisan League Party]] incumbent [[Heidi Heitkamp]] and would instead run for re-election to the U.S. House.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hageman |first=John |url=http://www.grandforksherald.com/news/4388374-cramer-names-campaign-manager-re-election-bid |title=Cramer names campaign manager for re-election bid |publisher=Grand Forks Herald |date=2018-01-15 |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref> However, on February 15, 2018, Cramer announced that he had changed his mind and would run for the U.S. Senate in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Jessica|title=GOP Gets Top Recruit To Run In Key North Dakota Senate Race|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/02/15/586110338/gop-gets-top-recruit-to-run-in-key-north-dakota-senate-race|accessdate=15 February 2018|publisher=NPR|date=February 15, 2018}}</ref> Odney advertising firm president Pat Finken serves as Cramer's campaign manager.<ref>{{cite web|author=JACK DURA Bismarck Tribune |url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/finken-leading-cramer-campaign/article_edd0170c-2015-53ab-bac5-3fcf9571bc77.html |title=Finken leading Cramer campaign &#124; Government, Politics and Elections |publisher=bismarcktribune.com |date=2018-03-22 |accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> On April 7,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kfyrtv.com/content/news/Rep-Kevin-Cramer-accepts-GOP-endorsement-479061623.html |title=Rep. Kevin Cramer accepts GOP endorsement |publisher=Kfyrtv.com |date=2018-04-07 |accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> Cramer secured the official endorsement of the North Dakota Republican Party. Three days later, his campaign announced it had raised $1.35 million in the first quarter of 2018, most of which was raised in late February and March.<ref>https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/apr/10/kevin-cramer-senate-campaign-raises-135m-1st-qtr/</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, ''The Washington Post'' reported that Cramer had contacted the White House to seek political help in his Senate campaign and that Cramer was upset that President [[Donald Trump]] had not publicly criticized incumbent Democratic Senator Heidi Heitkamp in the same way that he had criticized other Democrats.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/its-obscene-gop-candidate-seethes-as-trump-embraces-democratic-senatorsenator/2018/06/11/b8fa1f86-6b24-11e8-bf8c-f9ed2e672adf_story.html|title=\u2018It\u2019s obscene\u2019: GOP candidate seethes as Trump embraces Democratic senator|last=Sullivan|first=Sean|date=2018-06-11|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Cramer later publicly criticized White House staff and argued that Trump was refraining from criticizing Heitkamp because she was a woman.<ref name=\":0\" /> President Trump scheduled a June 2018 trip to North Dakota to campaign for Cramer, a trip which ''Politico'' reported \"could go a long way toward extinguishing tensions between the White House and the Senate hopeful.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Isenstadt |first1=Alex |title=Trump to campaign in N. Dakota for Rep. Kevin Cramer |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/15/trump-cramer-north-dakota-senate-650384 |accessdate=21 June 2018 |publisher=Politico |date=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCramer secured the Republican nomination for the United States Senate on June 12, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Press |first=Associated |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/republican-us-rep-kevin-cramer-wins-north-dakota-senate-primary-moves-on-to-face-incumbent-sen-heidi-heitkamp/2018/06/12/3d74350a-6ea7-11e8-b4d8-eaf78d4c544c_story.html?noredirect=on |title=Republican U.S. Rep. Kevin Cramer wins North Dakota Senate primary, moves on to face incumbent Sen. Heidi Heitkamp |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, a spokesman for the political network organized by the [[Koch brothers]] announced that they would not financially support Cramer's campaign because the brothers viewed Cramer as insufficiently supportive of free trade and fiscal conservatism, and because Cramer held other views inconsistent with those of the Koch brothers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Severns |first1=Maggie |title=Koch network snubs key GOP Senate candidate |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/30/koch-network-kevin-cramer-senate-749833 |accessdate=31 July 2018 |publisher=Politico |date=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cramer.house.gov/legislation/committees-and-caucuses|title=Committees and Caucuses|date=2012-12-13|website=Congressman Kevin Cramer|access-date=2016-06-01}}</ref>'''\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Environment and Economy|Subcommittee on Environment and the Economy]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n'''Caucus memberships'''\n* [[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|title=Members|author=|date=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|format=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Positions and tenure==\nIn February 2017, during President Trump's first address to a joint session of Congress, House Minority Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]] and a number of other female Democratic members of Congress wore white in protest against Trump. Cramer mocked the clothing protest, saying the Congresswomen dressed \"poorly\" and remarking, \"It is a syndrome. There is no question, there is a disease associated with the notion that a bunch of women would wear bad-looking white pantsuits in solidarity with Hillary Clinton to celebrate her loss. You cannot get that weird.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/kevin-cramer-democratic-women-white-pantsuits-235578|title=GOP lawmaker: \u2018Poorly dressed\u2019 Democratic women wore \u2018bad-looking white pantsuits\u2019|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Abortion ===\nCramer [[Anti-abortion movement|opposes abortion]]. He is a critic of [[Planned Parenthood]] and has called for cutting off public funding of the group.<ref>[http://www.gettyimages.com/detail/video/north-dakota-congressman-kevin-cramer-argues-that-his-news-footage/489190312 Kevin Cramer: North Dakota women not profitable for Planned Parenthood] (video of statement on U.S. House of Representatives floor, made available by [[Getty Images]]).</ref><ref>[https://cramer.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/cramer-statement-on-planned-parenthood-abortion-practices Cramer Statement on Planned Parenthood Abortion Practices] (press release), Office of U.S. Representative (July 16, 2015).</ref> In 2013, Cramer condemned the Supreme Court's decision in ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' and tied an uptick in mass shootings to the [[legalization of abortion]] and a demise in religious values.<ref name=\"TerkelSchoolShootings\">Amanda Terkel, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/16/kevin-cramer-school-shootings_n_3285328.html Kevin Cramer, North Dakota Congressman, Ties School Shootings to Abortion Legalization], ''The Huffington Post'' (May 16, 2013).</ref> This remark was criticized by the director of the North Dakota Democratic Party and in ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]''. Cramer said \"I was asked recently by a reporter if I am afraid that some people would attack me if I speak like this. And I said, 'No, I am not afraid they will, I am quite certain they will.\"<ref>Natasha Burton, [http://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/news/a12918/kevin-cramer/ Another Day, Another Crazy Abortion Claim from a Conservative Male Politician], ''Cosmopolitan'' (May 17, 2013).</ref><ref>[http://washington.cbslocal.com/2013/05/21/us-rep-cramer-criticized-for-linking-legalized-abortion-to-school-shootings/ US Rep. Cramer Criticized For Linking Legalized Abortion To School Shootings], Associated Press (May 21, 2013).</ref> In the same speech, Cramer stated of U.S. society: \"We have normalized perversion and perverted God's natural law.\"<ref name=\"TerkelSchoolShootings\" />\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nDuring his 2018 campaign, Cramer sought and received the support of the [[Public Advocate of the United States]], an anti-LGBT group which advocates for [[conversion therapy]] and ties homosexuality to [[pedophilia]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/14/politics/kfile-corey-stewart-kevin-cramer-anti-lgbt-survey/index.html|title=GOP Senate nominees Kevin Cramer, Corey Stewart sought support of extreme anti-gay group|last=CNN|first=Andrew Kaczynski,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> In an eight-question survey for the group, Cramer said he would oppose \"'Transgender Bathrooms' legislation and regulations \u2013 which have the effect of encouraging and protecting pedophiles\".<ref name=\":02\" /> Cramer also agreed that \"public schools should be 'prevented from brainwashing elementary school children with the Homosexual Agenda.'\"<ref name=\":02\" /> Cramer indicated support requiring schools to teach that there are only two genders and granting Christian businesses the right to not service same-sex weddings.<ref name=\":02\" /> A spokesman for Cramer said: \"Let's be clear. Congressman Cramer doesn't support the teaching of history with any special emphasis on any particular group. History is history and should be taught as such. Additionally, Kevin does not think transgender people are at all comparable to pedophiles \u2013 this a gross misinterpretation of the survey question.\"<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nCramer opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]] and condemned the [[Supreme Court of the United States]]' decision in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]''.<ref>Krista Boehm, [http://www.valleynewslive.com/home/headlines/The-first-same-sex-couple-to-grab-their-marriage-license-310218751.html The first same-sex couple to grab their marriage license], [[KVLY-TV]] (June 26, 2015).</ref><ref>[https://cramer.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/cramer-statement-on-supreme-court-same-sex-marriage-ruling Cramer Statement on Supreme Court Same Sex Marriage Ruling] (press release), Office of U.S. Representative Kevin Cramer (June 26, 2015).</ref><ref>Nick Smith, [http://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/n-d-delegation-split-on-gay-marriage/article_1bed85ba-dea8-11e2-9e5b-0019bb2963f4.html N.D. delegation split on gay marriage], ''Bismarck Tribune'' (June 26, 2013).</ref><ref name=\":02\" />\n\n=== Health care ===\nCramer opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act (Obamacare)]] legislation and has voted to repeal it without a replacement five times.<ref>John Hageman, [http://www.grandforksherald.com/news/politics/3774113-state-leaders-have-mixed-feelings-affordable-care-act-ruling State leaders have mixed feelings in Affordable Care Act ruling], ''Grand Fords Herald'' (June 25, 2015).</ref><ref>[https://cramer.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/us-house-votes-to-repeal-obamacare U.S. House Votes to Repeal Obamacare]  (press release), Office of U.S. Representative Kevin Cramer (February 3, 2015).</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://hpr1.com/index.php/feature/news/cramers-office-threatens-constituents/|title=Cramer\u2019s office threatens constituents|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=High Plains Reader, Fargo ND|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-15}}</ref> He has voted against health insurance protections for patients with [[Pre-existing condition|pre-existing conditions]], and has also voted against the expansion of [[Medicaid]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Cramer has said that the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]], the Republican bill to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act, which he supported would have prevented \"price discrimination\" against people with preexisting conditions; ''The Washington Post'' fact-checker described this assertion as false.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/09/19/did-house-gop-plan-prevent-price-discrimination-against-people-with-pre-existing-conditions/|title=Analysis {{!}} Would the House GOP plan have prevented \u2018price discrimination\u2019 against people with preexisting conditions?|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\nCramer supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] banning entry to the U.S. by citizens of seven Muslim-majority countries. He stated that \"I think what Donald Trump is doing is he's pulling America's head out of the sand and facing the reality that we have not been kept very safe by current immigration and refugee policies.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/29/heres-where-republicans-stand-on-president-trumps-controversial-travel-ban|title=Whip Count: Here\u2019s where Republicans stand on Trump's controversial travel ban|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|date=January 31, 2017|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> He has been described as one of Trump's allies in Congress and has pledged to be with Trump \"100 percent of the time\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-nation/2018/06/27/Trump-endorses-Kevin-Cramer-and-urges-North-Dakota-to-vote-out-Heidi-Heitkamp/stories/201806270263|title=Trump endorses Kevin Cramer and urges North Dakota to vote out Heidi Heitkamp|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment and energy ===\nCramer rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref name=\"Schreckinger\">Ben Schreckinger, [http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/donald-trump-climate-change-golf-course-223436 Trump acknowledges climate change \u2014 at his golf course], ''Politico'' (May 23, 2016).</ref><ref name=\"ParkDavenport\">Ashley Park & Coral Davenport, [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/21/science/donald-trump-global-warming-energy-policy-kevin-cramer.html New York Times: What Are Donald Trump's Views on Climate Change? Some Clues Emerge], ''New York Times'' (May 26, 2016).</ref> He has said that he would support a small [[carbon tax]] if the revenue went to [[research and development]] on clean fuel.<ref name=\"Schreckinger\"/><ref name=\"ParkDavenport\"/><ref>Evan Lehmann, [http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/meet-donald-trump-s-new-energy-adviser/ Meet Donald Trump's New Energy Adviser: Kevin Cramer calls himself a climate-change skeptic yet he might support a carbon tax], ''ClimateWire'' (republished by ''Scientific American'') (May 13, 2016).</ref> Cramer has been described by [[Reuters]] as \"one of America's most ardent drilling advocates.\"<ref name=\"Volcovici\">Valerie Volcovici, [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-trump-energy-idUSKCN0Y41ZP Trump taps climate change skeptic, fracking advocate as key energy advisor], Reuters (May 13, 2016).</ref> Cramer supports an increase in oil and gas drilling on [[public lands]] and supports cutting taxes for energy producers. He is opposed to what he characterizes as overreach by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref>Mark Drajem, [http://about.bgov.com/blog/get-your-energy-po0licy-ideas-to-kevin-cramer-asap/ Get your energy policy ideas to Kevin Cramer ASAP]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Bloomberg Government (May 16, 2016).</ref> In May 2016, [[Donald Trump]] asked Cramer to draft his campaign's energy policy.<ref name=\"Volcovici\" /> Cramer wrote Trump's energy plan, which focuses heavily on promoting [[fossil fuel]]s and weakening environmental regulation. The plan also vows to withdraw the U.S. from the [[Paris Agreement]] and repeal U.S. regulations aims at controlling the carbon emissions which cause climate change.<ref name=\"ParkerDavenport\">Ashley Parker & Coral Davenport, [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/27/us/politics/donald-trump-global-warming-energy-policy.html Donald Trump's Energy Plan: More Fossil Fuels and Fewer Rules], (May 26, 2016).</ref> Cramer was \"one of a handful of early Trump endorsers\" among U.S. House Republicans.<ref>Mike DeBonis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2016/05/11/paul-ryan-faces-intense-pressure-to-reconcile-with-donald-trump/ Paul Ryan faces intense pressure to reconcile with Donald Trump], ''The Washington Post'' (May 11, 2016).</ref>\n\n=== Food stamps ===\nCramer supports cuts in [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program]] (formerly the Food Stamp Program), and attracted controversy in 2013 when he cited a biblical quotation several times in support of Republicans' efforts to cut some $40 billion from the program over a ten-year period.<ref>Igor Bobic, [http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/gop-rep-on-food-stamp-cuts-if-anyone-is-not-willing-to-work-let-him-not-eat GOP Rep. Quotes Bible On Food Stamps: 'If Anyone Is Not Willing To Work, Let Him Not Eat'], ''TalkingPointsMemo'' (September 20, 2013).</ref><ref>[http://www.grandforksherald.com/content/rep-cramers-opponents-use-bible-verses-debate-food-stamp-cuts-look-toward-2014-election Rep. Cramer's opponents use Bible verses to debate food stamp cuts, look toward 2014 election], ''Grand Forks Herald'' (September 25, 2013).</ref>\n\n=== Gun policy ===\nCramer said that [[gun control]] would not have prevented the [[Orlando nightclub shooting]].<ref>Ted Fioraliso, [http://www.kfyrtv.com/content/news/Cramer-says-increased-gun-control-wouldnt-have-prevented-Orlando-shooting-383038541.html Cramer says increased gun control wouldn't have prevented Orlando shooting], [[KFYR-TV]] (July 14, 2016).</ref> In 2016, he criticized proposed gun control legislation, saying \"The problem isn't the U.S. Constitution. The problem is Islamic terrorism.\"<ref>Nick Smith, [http://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/hoeven-cramer-give-gun-legislation-cool-response/article_fca3294f-e226-5ebd-b7e4-f68a86d76a84.html Hoeven, Cramer give gun legislation cool response], ''Bismarck Tribune'' (June 21, 2016).</ref>\n\n=== Reservations ===\nIn 2013, at a forum on the [[Violence Against Women Act]] (VAWA), Cramer engaged in \"a testy exchange with Native American victim assistance leaders.\"<ref name=\"Johnson\">Luke Johnson, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/28/kevin-cramer-north-dakota-native-american_n_2974676.html \"Kevin Cramer, North Dakota Congressman, Regrets Berating Native American Counselors\"], ''Huffington Post'' (March 28, 2013).</ref><ref name=\"Schilling\">Vincent Schilling, [http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2013/04/01/north-dakota-congressman-kevin-cramer-allegedly-verbally-attacks-abused-native-womens North Dakota Congressman Kevin Cramer Allegedly Verbally Attacks Abused Native Women's Advocate], [[Indian Country Today Media Network]] (April 1, 2013).</ref> Cramer later issued a statement apologizing for his \"tone and rhetoric\" during the exchange.<ref name=\"Johnson\" /> Cramer voted to reauthorize the VAWA,<ref name=\"VotesVAWA\">[https://cramer.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-kevin-cramer-r-nd-votes-to-eliminate-constitutional Congressman Kevin Cramer (R-ND) Votes to Eliminate Constitutional Challenges to the Violence Against Women Act] (press release), Office of U.S. Representative Kevin Cramer (February 28, 2013).</ref> but opposed language in the act that would allow [[tribal court]]s to prosecute non-Natives \"for abusing or assaulting Native American women on Indian land.\"<ref name=\"Crane-Murdoch\">Sierra Crane-Murdoch, [https://www.hcn.org/issues/45.10/is-the-violence-against-women-act-a-chance-for-tribes-to-reinforce-their-sovereignty Is the Violence Against Women Act a chance for tribes to reinforce their sovereignty?], ''High Country Today'' (June 12, 2013).</ref> Cramer stated \"How could a non-Native man get a fair trial on a reservation?\"<ref name=\"Crane-Murdoch\" /> and questioned the constitutionality of the provision. He voted for an amendment to repeal the provision in question.<ref name=\"VotesVAWA\" />\n\n=== Comments on sexual assault allegations against Brett Kavanaugh ===\nIn 2018, Cramer said that both [[Anita Hill]]'s sexual harassment allegations against [[Clarence Thomas]] and [[Christine Blasey Ford]]'s sexual assault allegations against [[Brett Kavanaugh]] were \"absurd\". Cramer said that Ford's allegation was \"even more absurd\" than Hill's because the sexual assault that Ford described \"never went anywhere\" and because both Kavanaugh and Ford were intoxicated teenagers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/09/21/politics/kfile-cramer/index.html|title=GOP Senate nominee: Kavanaugh accusation 'absurd' because they were drunk and assault attempt 'never went anywhere'|last=CNN|first=Andrew Kaczynski and Christopher Massie,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> Cramer questioned whether Ford's sexual assault allegations against Kavanaugh would disqualify him from the Supreme Court even if they were found to be true; he added that if Kavanaugh were found to have lied in denying the allegations, that untruth would be disqualifying.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gop-rep-cramer-questions-whether-accusation-against-kavanaugh-should-disqualify-him-even-if-true/2018/09/25/c9aa7890-c069-11e8-9005-5104e9616c21_story.html|title=GOP Rep. Cramer questions whether accusation against Kavanaugh should disqualify him, even if true|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Taxes ===\nCramer voted to repeal the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]], which imposes a tax after the first several million dollars on the estate of a dead person.<ref>[https://cramer.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/cramer-house-passes-death-tax-repeal-act-of-2015 Cramer - House Passes Death Tax Repeal Act of 2015]  (press release), Office of U.S. Representative Kevin Cramer (April 16, 2015).</ref> Cramer supports [[Trump tariffs|Trump's 25% tax]] on many types of imports, which may have decreased sales for North Dakota's soybean industry in 2018, but has said he believes the long-term benefits of a trade war are worth it..<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestate.com/news/business/national-business/article218388335.html|title=North Dakota\u2019s Heitkamp attacks Cramer in new ad on tariffs|work=thestate|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/campaigns/kevin-cramer-has-home-field-advantage-in-north-dakota-senate-race-can-he-capitalize|title=Kevin Cramer has home field advantage in North Dakota Senate race. Can he capitalize?|date=2018-08-24|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCramer and his wife, Kris, have five children<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc6.psc.state.nd.us/commission/cramer.html|title=NDDOT - nd511|date=|website=Pc6.psc.state.nd.us|accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref> and four grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/cramer-to-stay-in-bismarck-with-family/article_337e690b-4a9b-50d2-b41e-b9809c26adf4.html |title=Cramer to stay in Bismarck with family &#124; Government, Politics and Elections |publisher=bismarcktribune.com |date=2018-02-27 |accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cramer.house.gov/ Congressman Kevin Cramer] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.kevincramer.org/ Kevin Cramer for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Dakota/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Kevin_Cramer_%5BR-AL%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|kevincramer02}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=C001096 | votesmart=444 | fec=H6ND00074 | congress=kevin-cramer/2144 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Jim Fuglie}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Tourism Director of North Dakota|years=1993\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=Bob Martinson}}\n{{s-bef|before=Chuck Stroup}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Economic Development Director of North Dakota|years=1997\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft|after=Lee Peterson}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Leo M. Reinbold|Leo Reinbold]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[North Dakota Public Service Commission]]|years=2003\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Julie Fedorchak]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=North Dakota\n| district=AL\n| before=[[